messages.content:
THOUGHT: The miscompile occurs because SLP sinks truncation across llvm.abs, effectively narrowing the abs operand type and changing semantics. Root min-bitwidth narrowing is not the culprit and must remain unchanged to satisfy existing tests. The correct fix is to treat llvm.abs as a barrier in the demotion (truncation-sinking) logic. I will:
- Ensure any previously added root min-bitwidth abs guard is removed.
- Insert a small helper IsAbsIntrinsic in the demotion section.
- Add a switch case for Instruction::Call that returns false when the node represents an abs intrinsic, preventing demotion across abs.
Then I will run the test suite via submit-patch.

```bash
python3 - << 'PY'
import pathlib, sys, re, textwrap, subprocess, os

p = pathlib.Path("llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp")
s = p.read_text()

# 1) Remove any accidental root min-bitwidth abs guard if present.
s = re.sub(r"[ \t]*// Avoid narrowing across llvm\.abs.*?(?=for \(Value \*Root : E\.Scalars\)\s*\{)", "", s, flags=re.S)

# 2) Find demotion section anchor and ensure helper is present.
anchor = "We can always demote truncations and extensions."
apos = s.find(anchor)
if apos == -1:
    print("ERROR: Demotion anchor not found", file=sys.stderr)
    sys.exit(1)

after_anchor = s.find("\n", apos)
insert_pos = after_anchor + 1 if after_anchor != -1 else apos

helper = textwrap.dedent("""\
    // Do not demote/sink truncations across llvm.abs intrinsic. Changing the
    // operand bitwidth of abs can alter semantics (e.g., computing abs in i32
    // instead of original i64 before trunc). Preserve abs width by treating it
    // as a barrier for truncation sinking.
    auto IsAbsIntrinsic = [](Value *V) {
      if (auto *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(V)) {
        if (const Function *F = CB->getCalledFunction())
          return F->isIntrinsic() && F->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::abs;
      }
      return false;
    };
""")

if "auto IsAbsIntrinsic" not in s[apos:apos+1200]:
    s = s[:insert_pos] + helper + s[insert_pos:]

# 3) Ensure switch has a Call case that blocks demotion across abs.
sw = s.find("switch (E.getOpcode())", apos)
if sw == -1:
    print("ERROR: Switch over E.getOpcode() not found", file=sys.stderr)
    sys.exit(1)

if "case Instruction::Call:" not in s[sw:sw+6000]:
    # Insert before Shl case if present, else after Freeze case.
    shl = s.find("case Instruction::Shl:", sw)
    if shl != -1:
        insertion_point = shl
    else:
        freeze = s.find("case Instruction::Freeze:", sw)
        insertion_point = s.find("\n", freeze) + 1 if freeze != -1 else s.find("\n", sw) + 1

    call_case = textwrap.dedent("""\
      case Instruction::Call: {
        // Do not demote across abs intrinsic; treat as non-demotable barrier.
        if (any_of(E.Scalars, IsAbsIntrinsic))
          return false;
        break;
      }
""")
    s = s[:insertion_point] + call_case + s[insertion_point:]

# Write back modifications.
p.write_text(s)

# Print a tiny confirmation snippet (few lines) around the call case.
lines = s.splitlines()
ln = next((i for i,l in enumerate(lines) if "case Instruction::Call:" in l), None)
if ln is not None:
    start = max(0, ln-3); end = min(len(lines), ln+8)
    print("\n".join(lines[start:end]))

# Run test suite via submit-patch
# Use subprocess to execute submit-patch and forward its output.
res = subprocess.run(["submit-patch"], text=True, capture_output=True)
print(res.stdout)
print(res.stderr, file=sys.stderr)
sys.exit(res.returncode)
PY
```

